pv_system_reason: Tired of paying increasing energy rates with the City of Austin and wanting to convert to a renewable source of energy.  City of Austin however has continued to change their rates and reimbursements such that I am once again paying monthly for my electricity.
pv_system_features_liked: That it provides clean energy.
pv_system_features_for_improvement: """City of Austin reimbursement structure needs to change such that owners of solar systems are no longer penalized for adopting a renewable energy system.  They've consistently reduced reimbursement rates while adding fees and increasing electricity rates which now means I have to pay for energy produced by panels that I own.  I paid to convert my house to a renewable source at my own expense and voluntarily reduced my consumption.  I find it ridiculous that I now pay a fee to the city for people who haven't converted or reduced their consumption (Community Benefit Charge).  Reimbursement rates need either to match the highest consumption rate charge or change to a tiered reimbursement that covers what gets generated.  The yearly zeroing out of credits is also ludicrous.  I'm pretty sure the city wouldn't zero out my bill if at the end of the year I owed them money.  I understand that Pecan street doesn't control these charges, but I hope that we can as a collective voice get energy policies that are ethical and make sense."""
pv_system_features_surprising: That the City of Austin could change their contractual obligations at the whim of the energy program manager.
pv_system_common_questions: How much did it cost?  Would I do it again if I had the choice?
pv_system_common_response: """I love my system, but if I had the choice to do it over again I'd completely remove my home from the grid so the city no longer had any say in what my energy costs.  It's counterproductive as a society to be so selfish with energy as some loss would occur in the battery storage system, but I wouldn't be producing energy so someone else could profit."""
pv_system_common_surprises: That the costs can be justified.
pv_owner_response: They share very similar concerns regarding the changes made by the city in reimbursement structure.  In general we all feel that it should be cost/profit neutral.
